00:00:01,280 --> 00:00:06,912
Before you create an initial product backlog, your team should have a shared vision of the product to develop

2
00:00:07,936 --> 00:00:11,520
while the product vision is not an official artifact of scrum

3
00:00:11,776 --> 00:00:14,080
it Can help set the goal that everybody can agrees on

4
00:00:14,848 --> 00:00:18,176
Customer management, the product owner and developer

5
00:00:18,944 --> 00:00:22,016
A good vision motivates the people working on the product

6
00:00:22,272 --> 00:00:24,576
And it helps make scope decisions later on

7
00:00:25,088 --> 00:00:27,392
What to put into the product and whatnot

8
00:00:28,160 --> 00:00:30,976
That's why it is relevant for backlog management as well

9
00:00:32,512 --> 00:00:36,352
As Ken Schwaber one of the fathers of Scrum once put it

10
00:00:36,608 --> 00:00:39,936
The minimum plan necessary to start a scrum project

11
00:00:40,192 --> 00:00:42,752
Consists of a vision and a product backlog

12
00:00:44,288 --> 00:00:48,128
It's the product owner who leads the effort to come up with a product vision

13
00:00:48,640 --> 00:00:52,224
It is created in close collaboration with the rest of the scrum team

14
00:00:52,480 --> 00:00:52,992
And other stakeholders

15
00:00:54,272 --> 00:01:00,160
Since this is a class about backlog management will focus on a very simple format for documenting the vision

16
00:01:00,416 --> 00:01:01,440
The vision statement

17
00:01:02,208 --> 00:01:04,000
A more sophisticated format

18
00:01:04,256 --> 00:01:05,536
to Create a product vision

19
